	  </figure></para><exercise id="secfhsst_id1066"><title> Naming alcohols 1 </title>
        <problem id="probfhsst_id1067">
        <para id="id84923">Give the IUPAC name for the following organic compound</para>
        <figure id="uid128">
          <media id="uid128_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CG12C1_056.png" id="uid128_onlineimage" width="120"><!-- NOTE: attribute width changes image size online (pixels). original width is 120. --></image>
            <image mime-type="application/postscript" for="pdf" src="../../media/CG12C1_056.eps" id="uid128_printimage"/>
          </media>
        </figure>
        
        </problem>
        <solution id="solfhsst_id1077"> <list id="listfhsst_id1077" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" class="stepwise">
        <item> <label> Identify the functional group </label>
        <para id="id84959">The compound has an -OH (hydroxyl) functional group and is therefore an alcohol. The compound will have the suffix -ol.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Find the longest carbon chain </label>
        <para id="id84967">There are three carbons in the longest chain. The prefix for this compound will be 'prop'. Since there are only single bonds between the carbon atoms, the suffix becomes 'propan' (similar to the alkane 'propane').</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Number the carbons in the carbon chain </label>
        <para id="id84976">In this case, it doesn't matter whether you start numbering from the left or right. The hydroxyl group will still be attached to the middle carbon atom, numbered '2'.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Look for any branched groups, name them and give their position on the carbon chain. </label>
        <para id="id84985">There are no branched groups in this compound, but you still need to indicate the position of the hydroxyl group on the second carbon. The suffix will be -2-ol because the hydroxyl group is attached to the second carbon.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Combine the elements of the compound's name into a single word in the order of branched groups; prefix; name ending according to the functional group. </label>
        <para id="id84995">The compound's name is propan-2-ol.
 </para>
        </item> </list> </solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="secfhsst_id1091"><title> Naming alcohols 2 </title>
        <problem id="probfhsst_id1092">
        <para id="id85024">Give the IUPAC name for the following compound:</para>
        <figure id="uid129">
          <media id="uid129_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CG12C1_057.png" id="uid129_onlineimage" width="148"><!-- NOTE: attribute width changes image size online (pixels). original width is 148. --></image>
            <image mime-type="application/postscript" for="pdf" src="../../media/CG12C1_057.eps" id="uid129_printimage"/>
          </media>
        </figure>
        
        </problem>
        <solution id="solfhsst_id1102"> <list id="listfhsst_id1102" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" class="stepwise">
        <item> <label> Identify the functional group </label>
        <para id="id85060">The compound has an -OH (hydroxyl) functional group and is therefore an alcohol. There are <emphasis effect="italics">two</emphasis> hydroxyl groups in the compound, so the suffix will be -diol.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Find the longest carbon chain </label>
        <para id="id85074">There are four carbons in the longest chain. The prefix for this compound will be 'butan'.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Number the carbons in the carbon chain </label>
        <para id="id85082">The carbons will be numbered from left to right so that the two hydroxyl groups are attached to carbon atoms with the lowest numbers.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Look for any branched groups, name them and give their position on the carbon chain. </label>
        <para id="id85090">There are no branched groups in this compound, but you still need to indicate the position of the hydroxyl groups on the first and second carbon atoms. The suffix will therefore become 1,2-diol.</para>
        </item> <item> <label> Combine the elements of the compound's name into a single word in the order of branched groups; prefix; name ending according to the functional group. </label>
        <para id="id85100">The compound's name is butan-1,2-diol.
 </para>
        </item> </list> </solution>
</exercise>
